4 The wife and I attended the soft opening today. The restaurant bills itself as French Inspired, but I noticed traditional Italian, Greek, as well as American fare. We started with a delicious Greek salad, full of olives, sweet yellow/red cherry tomato's, and feta. We tried the calamari, tender and succulent. The wife raved about her Seafood Risotto, served with shrimp, mussels, and diver's scallops. I had the osso buco over risotto. Delicious. The meat was tender, moist, and very flavorful. We ended up sharing a slice of ricotta cheesecake. Light and airy. I prefer a dense cheesecake, but all cheesecake is good. Unfortunately the wife and I rarely drink, but our waiter did mention 57 wines being available for service. We hope to return in about a week or so to see if the menu has changed. And we shall see if I can award Bistro 57 a fifth star once we have tried a few more dishes.
5 Initially I had to say I was bummed out that Pasta Cucina had to go because they had great food at great prices, all in a very beautiful restaurant. Well after dining here tonight, I'm like Pasta Cu-watchamacallit?! This new place has an awesome menu, mostly French inspired dishes along with some other things such as pasta as well.  Prices are unheard of! The average entree was $10-$15 with the most expensive thing on there being $24. Their sides which include grilled asparagus and haricot verts range from $3-$4. You can't find these prices anywhere else around the Vegas area!  I ordered the shepards pie which was huge. Very tasty with nice chunks of carrots, peas and onion. It had the slight taste of red wine which compliments the ground beef so well, all topped with mashed potatoes. There's just something so comforting about eating a meal with a spoon. And all this was only $10!  I tried the french onion and my friend ordered the potato leek soup and both were amazing. I'm already torn about which one i'm gonna get next time I'm there.   My friend ordered spaghetti bolognese with meatballs. The pasta was perfectly cooked al dente and the sauce had a generous amount of meat. We both are so used to meat sauces not having enough meat so that's why she ordered the meatballs. Next time, we'll know that it won't be necessary because for once we found a place that actually serves up a meaty meat sauce. Go figure, right?  To top it all off, we had the marscapone cheesecake that didn't stand a chance against us even though we said we were "full." It was too irresistable. Not as rich and dense as traditional cheesecake but that's what I loved about.  Service was awesome, shout out to Skyler! Manager and Chef came by to check on us. They even gave us a complimentary app of garlic bread with marinara that had a huge glob of goat cheese in it. They really are generous here. You are getting way more than your money's worth.  I can't wait to come back and try all the other things on the menu which included escargot, a real nicoise salad, beet salad, monte cristo, just to name a few. BTW they are open for breakfast, lunch and dinner.
5 I've eaten at this place twice now, once at breakfast and once at lunch. Breakfast is 7am-11am, FYI.  The breakfast menu isn't large by any means but it has everything you could want. I got the bagel with cream cheese and lox (smoked salmon). The bagel isn't a large one but it's just right. The lox is amazing. It's the best lox I've had on this side of the country and the best I've had since I went to a mom-and-pop bagel shop in NYC. The lox slices are large enough to cover the entirety of the bagel and then some. They also gave a more than ample amount of cream cheese. They also have a scrambled eggs and lox with caramelized onions and toast. It looked and smelled very tasty but I didn't get to have any.  For lunch I had the fish and chips. The chips were magnificent and the fish was perfectly cooked in a light breading. The chips had a crispy outside and a potato-y center and cooked just right. I don't know what kind of fish they use but it's probably cod or tilapia.  With both breakfast and lunch I had their caramel macchiato. Way better than Starbucks or Coffee Bean! Had just the right mix of flavor between coffee and caramel.  The serving sizes aren't small but they're not overly large, either. You'll get a decent full but not too full off the serving sizes.  The servers and management are very friendly and provide great service. The prices are some of the best for this style and calibre of restaurant in town. I couldn't recommend giving this place a try at least once!
